title: bouquet_toss
body:
A western [[wedding]] tradition where the [[bride]] tosses their wedding [[bouquet ]] to the unmarried women attending.  The woman who catches the bouquet is said to be the one who will be wed next.

The [[garter toss]] is the counterpart tradition for the groom and bachelors attending.

title: garter_toss
body: A western [[wedding]] tradition which involves two parts.  During the first part the [[bride]] sits on a chair and the [[groom]] then goes under her skirt to remove one of her garters either by hand or by tradition with his teeth.  The second part is the garter toss, where the garter is then tossed to the bachelors attending the wedding.  The bachelor who catches the garter is said to be the next person who'd become wed.  The garter toss is the counterpart to the bride's [[bouquet toss]].

title: evil_ryu
body:
[b]Evil Ryu[/b], whose full name is known as [b]Satsui no Hadou ni Mezameta Ryuu[/b] ([i]lit.[/i]"Ryu who has Awakened to the Surge of Killing Intent"), is a playable character in various [[Street Fighter]] games beginning with [[Street Fighter Zero (series)|Street Fighter Zero 2]]. He was originally introduced in a Street Fighter Zero manga series authored by [[Nakahira Masahiko]] and later adapted in the Street Fighter canon by [[Capcom]]. He is the version of [[Ryu (street fighter)|]] should he succumb to Satsui no Hadou, and depicts Ryu's struggle to resist the urge. Gameplay-wise, Evil Ryu has more powerful attacks than the original, strikes faster and possesses some of the attacks of [[Akuma (street fighter)|]]. The kanji 'Metsu' (滅) - meaning "destruction" - can be seen on his back when it appears after a Shun Goku Satsu finish.

title: adon_(street_fighter)
body:
[b]Adon[/b] ([i]katakana[/i]: [b]アドン[/b], [i]thai[/i]: [b]อาดอน[/b]) is a character from the [[Street Fighter]] series of fighting games. He has appeared in the first Street Fighter game, and notably the [[Street Fighter Zero (series)|Street Fighter Zero]] series. Adon also appears in [[street_fighter_iv_(series)|Super Street Fighter IV]].

Adon became [[sagat|Sagat's]] student three years after Sagat became God of Muay Thai. Frequently likened to a "lesser version of Sagat", even though he has strived to differentiate himself with more acrobatic techniques, Adon enters the first World Warrior tournament to prove he is more than that. The cocky Adon lets his guard down when he faces [[ryu (street fighter)|Ryu]], who takes him out with a single [[Shouryuuken]]. Afterwards, Ryu goes on to defeat Sagat, which leads to Adon's eventual breakdown. 

Adon is not mad at Ryu for defeating him, he is mad at Sagat for being unable to uphold Muay Thai's honor (conveniently forgetting how Ryu had bested him during the World Warrior tournament). He challenges Sagat for the title of God of Muay Thai and wins, but the enraged Sagat does so much damage to him in the fight that Adon has to be hospitalized for months. Adon's injuries eventually heal and a new fighter captivates his attention. Rumor reaches his ears of a fighter who has mastered the power that had enabled Ryu to win the first World Warrior Tournament. This fighter kills a man who was about to challenge Adon for his title. Adon sees this as a challenge. Knowing only that this [[akuma (street fighter)|mysterious fighter has red hair and wears a black gi with the symbol "Ten" on his back]], Adon swears to find him and test his strength.

title: carcano_m91/38
body:
After the Great War and the second war in Ethiopia, the Italian military eagerly searched for a new cartridge to replace the middling performance of 6.5x52mm Carcano. Aiming for higher penetration, flatter trajectory, and more damage, the Italians would ultimately come to the 7.35x51mm Carcano cartridge. This cartridge featured a Spitzer-style projectile instead of the 6.5 Carcano's round-nosed projectile. Using the same en-bloc clip-fed bolt-action design of the M91 Carcano, other notable changes in the M38 were cutting overall length by over ten inches and fixing the rear sights at a 200 meter distance, believing this would the average engagement distance in modern warfare.

Despite this ambition, the switch to 7.35 Carcano would become to strenuous and costly on logistics. Another issue included the Italian military's decision to chop the barrel of existing M1891s into M38s, ignoring how the old twist rate would affect the accuracy of the rifle with the newer, hotter ammunition, proving a detriment to a number of the rifles' accuracy. By mid 1940 the military would revert back to 6.5 Carcano, rebarreling most M38s with the few remaining 7.35 Carcano rifles relegated to auxiliary troops and paramilitary organizations. Under the new M91/38s designation, the rifle would continue production in Italy's earlier caliber of choice.

The M38 Carcano would serve as the backbone of the Italian army for much of World War II, though they weren’t shy about offering them to allies. Finland would accept many during the Winter War against the Soviet Union. Germany’s Afrika Corps would procure some M38s for themselves, rechambering them for 7.92x57mm Mauser. They would see combat throughout the Mediterranean and Eastern Fronts. Following the ousting of Benito Mussolini in 1943, some Italian troops in areas such as Greece and Yugoslavia would join the rebel troops and fight off the Germans. Since the end of World War II, these rifles have found their way into the hands of rebels and insurgents alike, seen most recently in conflicts such as the Libyan Civil War.

Since the end of the War, the Carcano has been a popular choice on the consumer market, particularly with hunting. With the short length, light weight, and the ability to mount an aftermarket scope on the rifle it was common to see it in the hands of hunters in the following decades alongside other wartime rifles.

body: The MGL is a multiple-shot weapon, intended to significantly increase a small squad's firepower when compared to traditional single-shot grenade launchers like the M203. title: crash_test_dummy
body:
A crash test dummy is a type of [[dummy]] that simulates a human in size, weight, and articulation that is used in vehicle crash tests.  Their most distinguishing feature is the visual reference marker composed of a circle divided into four alternating segments of black and yellow.  At least one of these markers is commonly placed on the side of the dummy's head.

body:
A manga adaptation of the original [[Mobile Suit Gundam]], written and illustrated by [[Yasuhiko Yoshikazu]]. Published from June 25, 2001 to June 25, 2011, and then followed by an adaptation of the [[mobile suit Gundam: cucuruz doan's island|Doan's Island]] episode that ran from June 25, 2016 to August 25, 2019.

The manga was partially adapted into a 6-episode series of OVAs released between 2015 to 2018. These OVA episodes primarily focused on a younger [[Char Aznable]], and his pre-OYW backstory. The OVAs were later recut into 13 TV-length episodes that aired in the 2019 Spring season.

title: mobile_suit_gundam:_cucuruz_doan's_island
body:
A [[Gundam]] movie released in June 2022, adapting the [[Mobile Suit Gundam]] episode of the same name.

The original episode is notorious for being the source of several of the most recognizable [[QUALITY]] instances from the series, and is such a sore spot for the creators that [[Tomino Yoshiyuki]] himself requested that it not be included in foreign releases of the series.

The episode was adapted into part of [[mobile suit Gundam the origin|The Origin]] from 2015 to 2019. This adaptation provided a lengthier backstory for [[Cucuruz Doan]] himself, and further context for characters involved in the original episode.

title: cicada
body:
A large [[bug|insect]] belonging to the superfamily [i]Cicadoidea[/i]. Notable for their large, veiny transparent wings and their loud droning mating call.

In Japan the presence and droning cries of the cicada is heavily associated with summer (particularly on hot days with muggy weather). As such the cicada or its call is often used to help set the scene for a story happening during summer. In North America, periodic cicadas are famous for appearing in huge numbers in regular intervals.

h4. See also

* "Wikipedia article":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cicada]

title: area_51
body:
Common nickname for a particular maximum-security [[United States Air Force|USAF]] research facility, situated within a large training range near [[Las Vegas]]. While it's known to have been previously used for high-tech aircraft development and Cold War espionage, the facility's [i]current[/i] purpose is a closely-guarded secret, which ironically makes it a very famous aspect of various conspiracy theories and general folklore around alien visitors to Earth.

In June 2019, a joke event known as ""Storm Area 51, They Can't Stop All Of Us":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Storm_Area_51 " ostensibly scheduled a raid of the facility for September of that year, notoriously encouraging people to try and dodge bullets by using the [[Naruto Run]]. It became such a viral phenomenon that local law enforcement had to explicitly warn people to stay away for their own safety.

When an image containing more than 256 colors is saved as a GIF, the color limitation of the GIF format creates artifacts (defects) such as [[dithering]] (e.g. post #720057) or [[color banding]] (e.g. the background of post #76332).

Note that despite artifacting in high-color images, GIFs have legitimate uses, such as for [[pixel art]], low-color [[Oekaki]] images, and animated images.

title: steel_square
body:
A [i]steel square[/i], also commonly referred to as a [i]framing square[/i] or [i]carpenter's square[/i], is a tool used in carpentry.  It is a long-armed square (a tool used for marking and referencing a 90° angle) consisting of a wider arm and shorter, narrower arm, that meet at a right angle.  Traditionally made of steel, they're also commonly now made of other materials such as aluminum.

The longer wider arm is two inches (51 mm) wide, and is called the blade; the shorter narrower arm, is one and a half inches (38 mm) wide, and is called the tongue. The square has many uses, including laying out common rafters, hip rafters and stairs.  It has a diagonal scale, board foot scale and an octagonal scale. On the newer squares there are degree conversions for different pitches and fractional equivalents.

title: periscope
body:
A periscope is an instrument for observation over, around or through an object or obstacle that prevents direct line-of-sight.  In its simplest form, it consists of an outer case with mirrors at each end set parallel to each other at a 45° angle. 

Periscopes are most commonly remembered for their use in [[submarine]]s, but have been used by the military in other areas such as trench warfare, gun turrets, and armored vehicles.  Periscopes in the use of submarines have gradually been replaced by the [i]photonics mast[/i], a similar device that replaces the direct mechanical line-of-sight with digital equipment and cameras.

title: white_thoroughbred_(kemono_friends)
body:
A [i][[Kemono Friends]][/i] character. One of many "Friends" in Japari Park. The Thoroughbred Trio were created for a promotion involving the Anime and the [[Japan Racing Association]]. They have since integrated with the wider franchise and the JRA moved on with [[umamusume|a different franchise]].

Horses and Thoroughbreds are better explained in [[Brown Thoroughbred (Kemono Friends)|]]'s page.

A white horse denotes a horse with a white coat (or a coat splotched with white) with pink skin, caused by a dominant white gene, usually created from a random fortuitous mutation. For this reason, white in Thoroughbreds is very rare and few thrive in the racetrack simply due to demographics (for example, only [[sodashi_(racehorse)|one white horse]] has ever won a 1st grade race and only as recently as 2020, this one eventually won two more races of that grade). They are not to be confused with gray horses, horses who, born as chestnut or bay, become lighter in color with age, eventually ending up with a white coat and dark skin.

White Thoroughbred is (naturally) a [[horse girl]] with long white hair resembling a mane in braids, wearing a white sports ensemble.

She is based off a piece of "genderswap fanart":/posts/2772926 of the V3 design done by the same artist.

V4 Flower retains most of the original piece's looks, resulting in an [[androgynous]] appearance. Her hair is kept shorter and more boyish, though it still retains the [[streaked_hair|streaked]] white/black color scheme. She wears black [[shorts]] with purple [[lace-up boots]] as well as a purple [[vest]] underneath her hood.

Official art: post #3490406

title: la_brava
body:
A villain from Boku no Hero Academia, whose real name is Manami Aiba.

She deeply cares about [[Gentle Criminal]], her one and only partner.

She's a short girl with magenta colored pigtails with permanent dark rings around her eyes and a striking outfit, consisting of various heart-shaped motifs, poofy pants, high-heeled boots and a bowtie.

Her quirk consists of powering up for a small amount of time the person she loves the most.

title: kamado_nezuko
body:
A main character from [[Kimetsu no Yaiba]] and the sister of [[Kamado Tanjirou]]. She was a human before getting exposed to demon blood into her veins, eventually turning into a demon when her brother found her.

She has [[pink eyes]] and [[long hair|long]] [[black hair|black]] and [[brown hair]] and is often seen wearing a [[kimono]] and a [[bamboo]] muzzle around her mouth like a [[bit gag]].

[spoiler]When she goes into her "demon form", her eyebrows point downward with veins all around her head visible and stretching her skin and her pupils turn different. In this form she has a single horn but not the bamboo muzzle on.[/spoiler]

title: off-shoulder_leotard
body:
A [[leotard]] that is [i]naturally designed[/i] with a low and wide-cut neckline, not covering the shoulders or upper chest area, leaving them [[bare shoulders|bare]].

Off-shoulder leotards are meant to emphasize and accentuate the wearer's shoulders, [[collarbone]], and neck (or [[nape]]), with the sleeves of an off-shoulder leotard sitting on the upper arms instead of on top of the shoulders.

For the leotard to qualify for this tag, the sleeves [i]must be attached[/i] to the leotard. If they are not, then it is a [[strapless leotard]] with [[detached sleeves]].

Off-shoulder leotards and [[strapless leotard]]s are mutually exclusive to each other.

title: jure_of_healing
body:
Jure of Healing is the goddess of restorative magic in [[Elona]], and the goddess whose religion seems most traditionally similar to Christianity, including a "Festival of Jure" that happens during December.  (Which also functions as a membership drive/evangelization for her religion.)  Her divine weapon is also The Holy Lance, a spear that heals its user, a reference to the Christian belief that the spear that pierced the side of Christ became a holy relic capable of miracles.

She appears as a woman with white feathery [[wings]], a yellow dress and broad-topped hat, and [[green hair]] with a copper-colored stripe.  

Jure is, unusual for her seeming Christian inspiration, a [[tsundere]], and seems quite insecure around her own followers.  In stereotypical tsundere fashion, she stutters while saying that she really doesn't want you to be her follower, or denying that she's happy when you give her sacrifices or that she's been lonely if you have closed the game for a while.

Her preferred sacrifices are ores, which are the subject of a few jokes, as ores can be both valuable materials like rubynus crystals, or useless junk stones.  Nearly every player sacrifices junk stones to her, however, as they are rewarded just the same, and are far less valuable and more easily found in literally any random field by the side of the road.  Hence, it's common to see Jure being inundated with junk stone sacrifices.

Jure's servants are the [[Defender (elona)|]]s.

title: black_angel_(elona)
body:
A divine servant character of the sadistic [[Lulwy of Wind]], [[Black Angel (elona)|]]s are given as rewards to Lulwy's faithful in the game [[Elona]].  

Their salient characteristics are their [[purple hair]] in [[twintails]],  with black ribbons, their characteristic [[black wings]], blue frilly dress, and black boots.  

The twintails, alone, give many artists a "tsundere" impression of Black Angel, although given her master's sadism, some show her quite masochistic, as well.  

Like most Elona characters, they are randomly named upon spawning, and Black Angel is just a class name.  In-game, they appear as something like "Anita the black angel". 

As the servant of the most archery-centric goddess, black angels are most commonly wielding a [[bow (weapon)|]], but can use any melee weapon.  Their specialty is a self-targeting speed boost, which lets them rain arrows upon their opponents in rapid succession.

title: lind
body:
Lind is an [[Aa Megami-sama]] character, and a Valkyrie: goddess that belongs to Heaven's Fighting Wings combat unit. In the manga she's the fifth goddess to show up in [[Morisato Keiichi|Keiichi's]] house, during an emergency, although in the anime, she makes a brief appearance before that, making her the fourth goddess to appear on screen. 

Serious, stoic and all business like, are the best ways to describe Lind, even though she does have a sensitive side to her as well. Lind had to struggle for quite some to overcome a rather unusual condition that left her with an angel that possessed one wing (and even referred to as the [i]"One winged angel"[/i]) but in the end it was proven that she had a pair of twin angels. Being unable to support both of them at the same time, Lind pushed herself harder than any other Valkyrie, earning herself a rather fearsome reputation among Heavens. Eventually, Lind overcomes her difficulties, and thanks to the involvement of Keiichi in the entire process, she likens to refer to him as her lifelong friend.

Defenders are one of the few servants that are always male.

title: black_cat_(elona)
body:
Servant of [[Ehekatl of Luck]], luck goddess of [[Elona]], black cats can become party members as rewards for those who are faithful to the quirky goddess. 

Appearance-wise, the black cat is... well, a black [[cat]]. 

Amusingly, due to the way that the race of all servants is "servant" race, black cats have a humanoid form, size, and weight in game stats terms, even though they appear as cats.  This means they can wear plate armor and wield sword and shield or use guns.  

Their special ability is "licking" the items dropped by some of the creatures they kill, adding one extra magical effect to the randomly-generated equipment.

Black cats can either be male or female... although there's no particular difference unless they are evolved in Elona+, where male black cats become black [[lion]]s, and female black cats become catgirls.  

Like many characters in Elona, black cat is just a "class name" for the character, and they have a randomly generated personal name upon spawning.  Hence, they would appear as something such as "Sezluk the black cat".

[b]Kamikaze Kaitou Jeanne[/b] (also known as [b]Phantom-Thief Jeanne[/b]) is a fantasy shoujo manga series written and illustrated by [[Tanemura Arina]]. The story is about the adventures of a high school girl, [[Kusakabe Maron]], who is the reincarnation of [[Jeanne D'Arc]] and transforms into a [[magical girl]] "kaitou":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kait%C5%8D#Genre to collect the scattered pieces of God's power which are also coveted by [[demon]]s hiding in beautiful art works.

The manga was published by [i]Shueisha[/i] in [i]Ribon[/i] between February 1998 and July 2000. The individual chapters were collected and published in seven tankoubon volumes. It is licensed for English-language release by CMX Manga. The series was adapted by [[Toei Animation]] as a 44-episode anime television series that was broadcast on [i][[TV Asahi]][/i] from February 1999 to January 2000. The series was re-issued by [i]Shueisha[/i] in 2007, with all chapters fitting into only 6 volumes, instead of the original 7; all volumes had new covers.

title: pythia
body:
[b]Pythia[/b] (pronounced /ˈpɪθiə/ or /ˈpaɪθiə/, Greek: Πυθία [pyːˈtʰi.a]), commonly known as [b]the Oracle of Delphi[/b], was the priestess at the Greek Temple of Apollo at Delphi, located on the slopes of Mount Parnassus. Pythia was widely credited for her prophecies inspired by God [[Apollo (mythology)|]]. 

The Delphic [[Oracle (ancient greece)|]] was established in the 8th century BCE. The last recorded response was given during AD 393, when the emperor Theodosius I ordered pagan temples to cease operation.

During this period the Delphic Oracle was the most prestigious and authoritative oracle among the Greeks.

title: quetzalcoatl_(mythology)
body:
Ancient God from the [[maya_(culture)|Mayan]] and [[Aztec]] cultures.

Its name literally means "Feathered Serpent" in the [[Nahuatl]] language.

One of the many ancient representations of this god was a bearded white man. Since the sixteenth century, it has been widely held that the Aztec Emperor [[Moctezuma II]] initially believed the landing of [[Hernan Cortes]] (a bearded white Spaniard man himself) in 1519 to be Quetzalcoatl's return, thus facilitating the subsequent "Conquest of Mexico" and the defeat of his Aztec Empire. 

Some Mormons even believe that Quetzalcoatl was historically [[jesus|Jesus Christ]], who visited America in ancient times.

He appears with a red [[robe]], (literally) flaming red hair, and a [[staff]].  (However, his design was only finalized later in development, so not all pictures of him agree.)

Personality-wise, he is a pompous and overbearing sort.

In vanilla Elona, he preferred a [[staff]] as his sacrifice, (which is a relatively uncommon weapon drop,) but in Elona+, this was changed to the much more common [[wand]]/[[rod]] item type.

His servant is the [[Exile (elona)|]].

title: xipe_totec
body: [b]Xipe Totec[/b] translates as [i]"Our lord the flayed one"[/i]. He is the [[Aztec]] god of life-death-rebirth, agriculture, vegetation, the east, disease, spring, goldsmiths, silversmiths and the seasons.

title: kumiromi_of_harvest
body:
Kumiromi of Harvest is the god of agriculture in [[Elona]].

Appearance-wise, his salient features are a green tunic, a green jester's hat, short [[brown hair]], white feathery [[wings]], and rather feminine appearance.  (There was initially some confusion as to his actual gender.)  He often wields his characteristic [[scythe]].

Personality-wise, he is a quiet sort that generally enjoys nature and watching over the growth of living things.  He only speaks complete sentences when talking about enjoying nature.  He admonishes his followers for spreading death, unlike most other gods.  His comments imply he is a former lover of [[Ehekatl of Luck]]'s, but her personality transformed, and they grew distant.  Kumiromi makes comments mourning this change on occasion.  Unlike most gods, rewards for following him are crafting-based skills and items.

Kumiromi does have what appears to be a dark side, however, and bears a grudge against those who betray him for another god or attack him, turning apparently [[yandere]] in the process, although he becomes no less terse about it.

His favored sacrifices are [[seed]]s and any form of [[vegetable]], even cooked, rotten, or rotten cooked ones.  Players that serve him often cook rotten vegetables and sacrifice them to him to train their cooking and not waste rotten food.  (Seeds are too rare and valuable to sacrifice.)

His servants are the [[cute_fairy_(elona)|cute fairies]].

title: opatos_of_earth
body:
Opatos of Earth is the god of strength in [[Elona]].  

He appears as a muscle-bound masculine figure that has giant stone [[wings]], is walking apparently out of a rock formation, or else has legs that disappear into stone, and inhumanly long arms made of stone. He wears a [[blindfold]]. He has long [[blue hair]], but some artists show it as brown, as well.

He tends to be a jovial sort, laughing even when angry.  Reckless and emotional, he is portrayed as the sort who acts upon feeling, and rarely thinks things through.  

He likes ore as his sacrifices, and he gives out a hammer as his divine weapon.

His servants are the [[golden_knight_(elona)|Golden Knights]].

title: mani_of_machine
body:
God of machines in [[Elona]].  He has a laid-back and level-headed personality.  He claims that the replacement of all organic life with machinery is an inevitability in some of his dialogue, but otherwise does not show any hostility towards anyone besides some rivalry towards the other gods.  

Appearance-wise, his salient features are white hair, and red eyes on a handsome humanoid head, with the rest of his body being clearly mechanical, with a black armored torso covered by black clothing and a [[cape]].  His metallic hands and torso have [[doll joints]].

His preferred sacrifice is a [[gun]], and his personal weapon he gives to players who are exceptionally devoted is a type of [[shotgun]] called the Winchester Premium.

His servants are the [[Android (elona)|]]s.

title: exile_(elona)
body:
The [[exile_(elona)|Exile]] is the divine servant of [[Itzpalt of Element]], the god of magic in the game [[Elona]].  As such, they are the only wizard-type servants in the game.  Servants can become party members as a divine reward when the player has a high enough devotion in a given deity's religion.  

In-game, the exiles appear as red-robed figures whose face is obscured by a hood, but which have [[third eye|three]] [[red eyes]], and a staff held by a strangely gray arm.  Different artists portray them differently, sometimes as long-haired and otherwise handsome characters with gray cancerous-looking lesions or partly petrified characters.  

In Elona+, they have one of the most sexually dimorphic evolutions of all the pets.  Male exiles turn into black [[dragon]]s, while female exiles turn into beautiful, but still three-eyed [[witch]]es in moderately revealing outfits, as opposed to their fully-hidden figures before. 

Like most Elona characters, Exile is just a "class name", and their actual names will be randomly generated upon spawning.  Hence, in-game, they would appear as something like "Omikka the exile".
